diff --git a/test/api/test_prepared_api.cpp b/test/api/test_prepared_api.cpp
index 74da545453bc..985fe9c0af54 100644
--- a/test/api/test_prepared_api.cpp
+++ b/test/api/test_prepared_api.cpp
@@ -130,9 +130,9 @@ TEST_CASE("Alter table and prepared statements", "[api]") {
 	// we can alter the type of the column
 	REQUIRE_NO_FAIL(con2.Query("ALTER TABLE a ALTER i TYPE BIGINT USING i"));
 
-	// after the table is altered, the return types change, so we fail executing the statement
-	REQUIRE_FAIL(prepared->Execute(12));
-	REQUIRE_FAIL(prepared->Execute(12));
+	// after the table is altered, the return types change, but the rebind is still successful
+	result = prepared->Execute(12);
+	REQUIRE(CHECK_COLUMN(result, 0, {12}));
 }
 
 TEST_CASE("Test destructors of prepared statements", "[api]") {
@@ -273,9 +273,6 @@ TEST_CASE("Test prepared statement parameter counting", "[api]") {
 	auto p4 = con.Prepare("SELECT $1::int, $2::string");
 	REQUIRE(p4->success);
 	REQUIRE(p4->n_param == 2);
-
-	auto p5 = con.Prepare("SELECT $2::int, $2::string");
-	REQUIRE(!p5->success);
 }
 
 TEST_CASE("Test ANALYZE", "[api]") {
diff --git a/test/sql/alter/alter_type/test_alter_type_dependencies.test b/test/sql/alter/alter_type/test_alter_type_dependencies.test
index f9032102cb65..9abce8a8dbdb 100644
--- a/test/sql/alter/alter_type/test_alter_type_dependencies.test
+++ b/test/sql/alter/alter_type/test_alter_type_dependencies.test
@@ -13,13 +13,39 @@ statement ok
 PREPARE v1 AS SELECT * FROM test
 
 # we can run the statement
-statement ok
+query II
 EXECUTE v1
+----
+1	1
+2	2
 
 # now change the type of "i" to varchar
 statement ok
 ALTER TABLE test ALTER i TYPE VARCHAR USING i::VARCHAR
 
-# executing the prepared statement now results in an error: the return types have changed
-statement error
+# executing the prepared statement now works as the alter type has not broken the query
+query II
 EXECUTE v1
+----
+1	1
+2	2
+
+statement ok
+ALTER TABLE test ALTER i TYPE INTEGER USING i::INTEGER
+
+# do the same, but this time the prepared statement depends on the type
+statement ok
+PREPARE v2 AS SELECT i+$1 FROM test
+
+query I
+EXECUTE v2(1)
+----
+2
+3
+
+statement ok
+ALTER TABLE test ALTER i TYPE VARCHAR USING i::VARCHAR
+
+# this now results in an error when rebinding
+statement error
+EXECUTE v2
\ No newline at end of file

+6	1	0	0	0	0	0.000000	0.000000	04/01/09	0	2009-04-01 00:00:00

+explain VACUUM

+statement ok

problem_statement:
Update Performance - executemany execution time is unexpectedly slow
I have been testing some UPDATE queries and the performance is slow.  For reference I am running version 0.2.9 on Windows 10.  

The query itself is pretty simple:

```
UPDATE main.users 
SET updated_at = ?
WHERE id = ? AND database = ?
```

I wrap the query in a single call to `con.executemany` and supply that values for updated_at, id, and database as a list of lists (id and database are composite keys for the table main.users).

The time to execute takes much longer than what I expected (longer than it takes to populate the entire table) given the relatively small payload.  Here is a summary of the performance:

|   rows_updated|   table_size |   time (s) |
|----------------:|-------------:|-----------:|
|          1,937 |      60,730 |       3.94 |
|          1,956 |   23,930,564 |     588.5  |
|          2,895 |     942,484 |      44.4  |
|          2,935 |   23,930,564 |     863.0  |
|          4,608 |    1,052,501 |      94.7  |
|          5,715 |    1,752,080 |     138.8  |
|          8,091 |    2,151,138 |     235.2  |
|         10,356 |    5,349,655 |     651.3  |

A bit surprised how much the execution time seems to depend on table size rather than number of rows updated. Was hoping someone can maybe give me some pointers on how to improve performance in this particular case and an explanation why performance is suffering so much.
SIGSEGV in duckdb_jdbc
#### What happens?
Seeing segvs with DuckDB seemingly related to the `Expression` class.

#### To Reproduce
Unable to reproduce. Unfortunately we don't have the SQL queries available. At this point we only have some basic stack information. No core file was produced either.

and

hints_text:
`executemany` uses prepared statements, and conditions with prepared statements are not converted into index scans currently, so this will run thousands of full scans on the table instead of using the index. This should explain the performance as it is basically a function of the table size and the amount of rows updated.

A quick fix would be to use a string replace instead for now and run the queries separately, as this should cause the index scans to be used correctly, but this should be properly fixed in the system itself.
OK, so if I understand correctly you are suggesting I do something like:

```
UPDATE schema.table
SET col = REPLACE(col, pattern1, pattern2)
WHERE col LIKE pattern1
```

This isn't exactly what I'm looking for, but I suppose I could make it work.  Do you think that this issue could be resolved within the next few releases?
I'm suggesting doing string replacement in the SQL string as a work-around instead of using prepared statements, e.g. something like this:

```py
con.execute(f"""
UPDATE main.users 
SET updated_at = {update_id}
WHERE id = {id} AND database = {database_id}
""")
```

Ah OK.  Thank you for the clarification. 
I tried implementing this with some success, unfortunately my machine seems to be running out of memory now.  DuckDB seems to really struggle with memory management even for databases under 10 GB.  If you know any tricks to help manage it would be very much appreciated.
Perhaps try reducing the memory limit (e.g. `PRAGMA memory_limit='XGB'`). Indexes are not buffer managed yet and hence can cause excess memory usage past the memory limit which can cause these issues.
Is this effectively the same as doing SET MAX_MEMORY = 'XGB'?
No, `SET MAX_MEMORY` has no effect on memory usage. The `SET` command is not yet used for most options (I believe it is only used for the S3 connector right now). Did you perhaps see this syntax somewhere in the documentation? If so, where?

first response in [this](https://github.com/duckdb/duckdb/issues/2349) thread
Thanks, I have updated the syntax there. In general the `SET` command should be extended to reject unknown settings as this can be quite confusing. I will have a go at that.
I just gave it a spin with both `PRAGMA memory_limit = '0.2GB'` and `PRAGMA memory_limit = '1GB'` and the kernel is still crashing.  Am I correct that a connection to the database must first be established before executing this statement?
You can pass a config object to the database   to set this before startup (see e.g. [here](https://github.com/duckdb/duckdb/blob/master/tools/pythonpkg/tests/fast/api/test_config.py)) and set the max_memory option.
Still no luck.  I tried with `con = duckdb.connect('db.db', config={'max_memory': '0.2GB'})` but opening the connection in a Jupyter Notebook still uses around 5 GB of memory.  This is on version 0.2.9
As mentioned before indexes are not buffer managed yet and do not count towards the memory limit, if you are using indexes then it is expected that the memory limit is exceeded in this manner currently.
Would it be possible to batch your updates? That may help the performance, but not the memory. However, maybe it would be fast enough that you would no longer need the index (which would help the memory). 

You could queue your updates up in Python and process them in DuckDB by inserting the new values into a temporary table, then doing an UPDATE FROM statement. The link below has an UPDATE FROM example also.

`
CREATE TEMP TABLE new_values AS 
Select 1 as key, 123 as value UNION ALL
Select 2 as key, 456 as value

UPDATE destination_table 
SET value = new_values.value 
FROM new_values 
WHERE destination_table.key = new_values.key
`

https://github.com/duckdb/duckdb/issues/1881
It's possible.  I will give it a shot and see how it compares to above.  Regarding the indexes, [DuckDB documentation](https://duckdb.org/docs/sql/indexes) states:

> - A min-max index is automatically created for columns of all general-purpose data types.

> - An Adaptive Radix Tree (ART) is mainly used to ensure primary key constraints and to speed up point and very highly selective (i.e., < 0.1%) queries. Such an index is automatically created for columns with a UNIQUE or PRIMARY KEY constraint and can be defined using CREATE INDEX.

So I don't see how there is any way to turn the indexes on or off.  Seems to me like they are always on?
Sorry to leave this issue hanging for so long.  After tinkering around it appears that the crashes were unrelated to the memory usage by the indexes and were instead related to a bug in the PyRelation object that was resolved by upgrading from v0.2.9 to v0.3.0.  I have re-run the update queries without using `executemany` and the update times no longer depend on the size of the table being updated.  See the table below for some statistics:

|   rows_updated|   table_size |   time (s) |
|----------------:|-------------:|-----------:|
|          3,143 |      24,324,315 |       7.04 |
|          1,007 |   23,930,564 |     1.72  |
|          782 |     3,545,319 |      1.41  |

Perhaps it's not a bad idea to keep the issue open as long as the issues with `executemany` persist.  I will re-name the title to something a bit more descriptive.
In looking at this further, the problem appears to be some sort of memory corruption. I've run a reproduction and gotten many different errors, from seg faults, to parameter bind errors to different `INTERNAL` errors.

You can find a reproduction at https://github.com/michaeljohnalbers/duckdb-issue-reproduction. There are some more notes in the README.
The following seems to provide a pretty good minimal reproduction. While it doesn't necessarily seg fault, when run with valgrind there are many errors (read after free).
```c++
int main(int argc, char **argv) {
  std::cout << "Starting DuckDB test" << std::endl;

  auto db = std::make_unique<duckdb::DuckDB>(nullptr);
  duckdb::Connection connection(*db);

  std::cout << "Creating table" << std::endl;
  connection.Query("CREATE table T1(A0 TIMESTAMP, A1 INTEGER, A2 VARCHAR, A3 VARCHAR, A4 INTEGER, A5 DOUBLE)")->Print();

  std::cout << "Preparing statement" << std::endl;
  std::vector<std::unique_ptr<duckdb::SQLStatement>> statements = connection.ExtractStatements("SELECT (SUM(CASE WHEN ((T1.A2 = ($1)::text) AND (T1.A3 = ($1)::text)) THEN T1.A4 ELSE (0)::int END) / ((SUM(CASE WHEN ((T1.A2 = ($1)::text) AND (T1.A3 = ($1)::text)) THEN T1.A4 ELSE (0)::int END) + SUM(CASE WHEN ((T1.A2 = ($2)::text) AND (T1.A3 = ($1)::text)) THEN T1.A4 ELSE (0)::int END)))::float8) AS A00036933 FROM T1");
  std::unique_ptr<duckdb::PreparedStatement> statement = connection.Prepare(std::move(statements.back()));

  std::cout << "Exiting." << std::endl;

  return 0;
}

```
Thanks for the reductions & investigation. That is very useful. I will have a look.
